</p><p>Convolution has applications that include <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=3D"Probability">probability</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statisti=
cs</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acoustics" title=3D"Acoust=
ics">acoustics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectroscopy" =
title=3D"Spectroscopy">spectroscopy</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Signal_processing" title=3D"Signal processing">signal processing</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_processing" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Image processing">image processing</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_vision" title=3D"Computer vision">comput=
er vision</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_perceptio=
n" title=3D"Visual perception">human vision</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Geophysics" title=3D"Geophysics">geophysics</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engineerin=
g</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">=
physics</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equa=
tion" title=3D"Differential equation">differential equations</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
onvolution#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The convolution can be defined for functions on <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space" title=3D"Euclidean space">Euclidean s=
pace</a> and other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_(mathemat=
ics)" title=3D"Group (mathematics)">groups</a> (as <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_structure" title=3D"Algebraic structure">algebra=
ic structures</a>).<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" sty=
le=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wik=
ipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"=
This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2017)">citation n=
eeded</span></a></i>]</sup> For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Periodic_function" title=3D"Periodic function">periodic functions</a=
>, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete-time_Fouri=
er_transform" title=3D"Discrete-time Fourier transform">discrete-time Fouri=
er transform</a>, can be defined on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a> and convolved by <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_convolution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Periodic convolution">periodic convolution</a>. (See row 18 at <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DTFT#Properties" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"DTFT">DTFT =C2=A7&nbsp;Properties</a>.) A <i>discrete convolution</i> c=
an be defined for functions on the set of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integers</a>.
</p><p>Generalizations of convolution have applications in the field of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_analysis" title=3D"Numerica=
l analysis">numerical analysis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Numerical_linear_algebra" title=3D"Numerical linear algebra">numerical=
 linear algebra</a>, and in the design and implementation of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_impulse_response" title=3D"Finite impulse=
 response">finite impulse response</a> filters in signal processing.<sup cl=
ass=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;"=
>[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" ti=
tle=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs reference=
s to reliable sources. (October 2017)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup=
>
</p><p>Computing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_funct=
ion" title=3D"Inverse function">inverse</a> of the convolution operation is=
 known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deconvolution" title=3D"=
Deconvolution">deconvolution</a>.
</p>
