<p>The convolution of two finite sequences is defined by extending the sequ=
ences to finitely supported functions on the set of integers. When the sequ=
ences are the coefficients of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomials</a>, then the coefficients of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_multiplication" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial multiplication">ordinary product of =
the two polynomials</a> are the convolution of the original two sequences. =
This is known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cauchy_produc=
t" title=3D"Cauchy product">Cauchy product</a> of the coefficients of the s=
equences.
</p><p>Thus, when <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>g</span> is non-zero over a finite interval [-M,+M] (representing, for ins=
tance, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_impulse_response" =
title=3D"Finite impulse response">finite impulse response</a>), a finite su=
mmation may be used:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
