hmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">integers modulo <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>N</i></span></a>.
</p><p>Circular convolution arises most often in the context of fast convol=
ution with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transfor=
m" title=3D"Fast Fourier transform">fast Fourier transform</a> (FFT) algori=
thm.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fast_convolution_algorithms=
">Fast convolution algorithms</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DConvolution&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"E=
dit section: Fast convolution algorithms"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In many situations, discrete convolutions can be converted to circular c=
onvolutions so that fast transforms with a convolution property can be used=
 to implement the computation. For example, convolution of digit sequences =
is the kernel operation in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multipl=
ication" title=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a> of multi-digit numbers=
, which can therefore be efficiently implemented with transform techniques =
(<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#CITEREFKnuth1997">Knu=
th 1997</a>, =C2=A74.3.3.C; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convol=
ution#CITEREFvon_zur_GathenGerhard2003">von zur Gathen &amp; Gerhard 2003</=
a>, =C2=A78.2).
</p><p><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#math_Eq.1">E=
q.1</a></b> requires <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">N</span> arithmetic operations per output value and <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>N</i><sup>2</sup></span> operations for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> outputs. That can be significantly =
reduced with any of several fast algorithms. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Digital_signal_processing" title=3D"Digital signal processing">D=
igital signal processing</a> and other applications typically use fast conv=
olution algorithms to reduce the cost of the convolution to O(<span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span> log <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">N</span>) complexity.
</p><p>The most common fast convolution algorithms use <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform" title=3D"Fast Fourier transfor=
m">fast Fourier transform</a> (FFT) algorithms via the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Fourier_transform#Circular_convolution_theore=
m_and_cross-correlation_theorem" title=3D"Discrete Fourier transform">circu=
lar convolution theorem</a>. Specifically, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Circular_convolution" title=3D"Circular convolution">circular =
convolution</a> of two finite-length sequences is found by taking an FFT of=
 each sequence, multiplying pointwise, and then performing an inverse FFT. =
Convolutions of the type defined above are then efficiently implemented usi=
ng that technique in conjunction with zero-extension and/or discarding port=
ions of the output. Other fast convolution algorithms, such as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sch%C3%B6nhage%E2%80%93Strassen_algorithm=
" title=3D"Sch=C3=B6nhage=E2=80=93Strassen algorithm">Sch=C3=B6nhage=E2=80=
=93Strassen algorithm</a> or the Mersenne transform,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rad=
er1972_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
onvolution#cite_note-Rader1972-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> use fast Fourier transforms =
in other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Ring (mathematics)">rings</a>. The Winograd method is used as an altern=
ative to the FFT.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It signifi=
cantly speeds up 1D,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> 2D,<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and 3D<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cit=
e_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> convolution.
</p><p>If one sequence is much longer than the other, zero-extension of the=
 shorter sequence and fast circular convolution is not the most computation=
ally efficient method available.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Madisetti1999_21-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_=
note-Madisetti1999-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Instead, decomposing the longer sequen=
ce into blocks and convolving each block allows for faster algorithms such =
as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overlap%E2%80%93save_method=
" title=3D"Overlap=E2=80=93save method">overlap=E2=80=93save method</a> and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overlap%E2%80%93add_method" title=
=3D"Overlap=E2=80=93add method">overlap=E2=80=93add method</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Juang2004_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-Juang2004-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A hybrid convolut=
ion method that combines block and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Finite_impulse_response" title=3D"Finite impulse response">FIR</a> algorit=
hms allows for a zero input-output latency that is useful for real-time con=
volution computations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gardner1994_23-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-Gardner=
1994-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Domain_of_definition">Domai=
n of definition</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DConvolution&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: =
Domain of definition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The convolution of two complex-valued functions on <span class=3D"texhtm=
