:italic;">g</span> decay sufficiently rapidly at infinity in order for the =
integral to exist. Conditions for the existence of the convolution may be t=
ricky, since a blow-up in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">g</span> at infinity can be easily offset by sufficiently rapid de=
cay in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span>. =
The question of existence thus may involve different conditions on <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span>:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Compactly_supported_functio=
ns">Compactly supported functions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DConvolution&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=
=3D"Edit section: Compactly supported functions"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">f</span> an=
d <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</span> are <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_support" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Compact support">compactly supported</a> <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">conti=
nuous functions</a>, then their convolution exists, and is also compactly s=
upported and continuous (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convoluti=
on#CITEREFH%C3%B6rmander1983">H=C3=B6rmander 1983</a>, Chapter 1). More gen=
erally, if either function (say <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">f</span>) is compactly supported and the other is <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locally_integrable_function" title=3D"Locall=
y integrable function">locally integrable</a>, then the convolution <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=E2=88=97<i>g</i></span> is well-defined and conti=
nuous.
</p><p>Convolution of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">f</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>g</span> is also well defined when both functions are locally square integ=
rable on <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</b></span> and supported on an interv=
al of the form <span class=3D"texhtml">[<i>a</i>, +=E2=88=9E)</span> (or bo=
th supported on <span class=3D"texhtml">[=E2=88=92=E2=88=9E, <i>a</i>]</spa=
n>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Integrable_functions">Integ=
rable functions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DConvolution&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: =
Integrable functions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The convolution of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">f</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>g</span> exists if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">f</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g=
</span> are both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue_integral=
" title=3D"Lebesgue integral">Lebesgue integrable functions</a> in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lp_space" title=3D"Lp space"><span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>L</i><sup>1</sup></span>(<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</b><s=
up><i>d</i></sup></span>)</a>, and in this case <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
f</i>=E2=88=97<i>g</i></span> is also integrable (<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#CITEREFSteinWeiss1971">Stein &amp; Weiss 1971</=
a>, Theorem 1.3). This is a consequence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Fubini%27s_theorem#Tonelli's_theorem" title=3D"Fubini's theorem">T=
onelli's theorem</a>. This is also true for functions in <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>L</i><sup>1</sup></span>, under the discrete convolution, or more =
generally for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#Conv=
olutions_on_groups">convolution on any group</a>.
</p><p>Likewise, if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i> =E2=88=88 <i>L</i><sup=
>1</sup></span>(<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</b><sup><i>d</i></sup></span>)=
&nbsp; and &nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i> =E2=88=88 <i>L</i><sup><i=
>p</i></sup></span>(<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</b><sup><i>d</i></sup></sp=
an>)&nbsp; where <span class=3D"texhtml">1 =E2=89=A4 <i>p</i> =E2=89=A4 =E2=
=88=9E</span>,&nbsp; then &nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>*<i>g</i> =
=E2=88=88 <i>L</i><sup><i>p</i></sup></span>(<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</=
b><sup><i>d</i></sup></span>),&nbsp; and
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \|{f}*g\|_{p}\leq \|f\|_{1}\|g\|_{p}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">=E2=80=96<!-- =E2=80=96 --><=
/mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi>f</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=88=97<!-- =E2=88=97 --></mo>
        <mi>g</mi>
        <msub>
          <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">=E2=80=96<!-- =E2=80=96 --=
></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>p</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=E2=89=A4<!-- =E2=89=A4 --></mo>
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">=E2=80=96<!-- =E2=80=96 --><=
/mo>
        <mi>f</mi>
