<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Functions_of_rapid_decay">F=
unctions of rapid decay</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DConvolution&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Functions of rapid decay"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In addition to compactly supported functions and integrable functions, f=
unctions that have sufficiently rapid decay at infinity can also be convolv=
ed. An important feature of the convolution is that if <i>f</i> and <i>g</i=
> both decay rapidly, then <i>f</i>=E2=88=97<i>g</i> also decays rapidly. I=
n particular, if <i>f</i> and <i>g</i> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Rapidly_decreasing_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rapidl=
y decreasing function">rapidly decreasing functions</a>, then so is the con=
volution <i>f</i>=E2=88=97<i>g</i>. Combined with the fact that convolution=
 commutes with differentiation (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Convolution#Properties">#Properties</a>), it follows that the class of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwartz_function" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Schwartz function">Schwartz functions</a> is closed under con=
volution (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#CITEREFStein=
Weiss1971">Stein &amp; Weiss 1971</a>, Theorem 3.3).
</p>
