<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution_algebra" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Convolution algebra">Convolution algebra</a></d=
iv>
<p>The convolution defines a product on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Linear_space" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear space">linear=
 space</a> of integrable functions. This product satisfies the following al=
gebraic properties, which formally mean that the space of integrable functi=
ons with the product given by convolution is a commutative <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_algebra" title=3D"Associative algebra"=
>associative algebra</a> without <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
dentity_element" title=3D"Identity element">identity</a> (<a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#CITEREFStrichartz1994">Strichartz 1994<=
/a>, =C2=A73.3). Other linear spaces of functions, such as the space of con=
tinuous functions of compact support, are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Closure_(mathematics)" title=3D"Closure (mathematics)">closed</a> u=
nder the convolution, and so also form commutative associative algebras.
</p>
