icial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligen=
ce</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3=
9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution=
#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> Though these are actually <b>cross-correlations<=
/b> rather than convolutions in most cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution#cite_note-=
40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup></li>
<li>In non-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_neural_netwo=
rk" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Artificial neural network">neural-networ=
k</a>-based <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_processing" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Image processing">image processing</a>
<ul><li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_image_processin=
g" title=3D"Digital image processing">digital image processing</a> convolut=
ional filtering plays an important role in many important <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a> in <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_detection" title=3D"Edge detect=
ion">edge detection</a> and related processes (see <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kernel_(image_processing)" title=3D"Kernel (image processi=
ng)">Kernel (image processing)</a>)</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optics" title=3D"Optics">op=
tics</a>, an out-of-focus photograph is a convolution of the sharp image wi=
th a lens function. The photographic term for this is <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bokeh" title=3D"Bokeh">bokeh</a>.</li>
<li>In image processing applications such as adding blurring.</li></ul></li=
>
<li>In digital data processing
<ul><li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytical_chemistry" t=
itle=3D"Analytical chemistry">analytical chemistry</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savitzky%E2%80%93Golay_smoothing_filter" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Savitzky=E2=80=93Golay smoothing filter">Savitzky=E2=80=
=93Golay smoothing filters</a> are used for the analysis of spectroscopic d=
ata. They can improve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal-to-no=
ise_ratio" title=3D"Signal-to-noise ratio">signal-to-noise ratio</a> with m=
inimal distortion of the spectra</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statis=
tics">statistics</a>, a weighted <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
oving_average" title=3D"Moving average">moving average</a> is a convolution=
.</li></ul></li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acoustics" title=3D"Acousti=
cs">acoustics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverberation" =
title=3D"Reverberation">reverberation</a> is the convolution of the origina=
l sound with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Echo_(phenomenon)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Echo (phenomenon)">echoes</a> from objects sur=
rounding the sound source.
<ul><li>In digital signal processing, convolution is used to map the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impulse_response" title=3D"Impulse respo=
nse">impulse response</a> of a real room on a digital audio signal.</li>
<li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_music" title=3D"=
Electronic music">electronic music</a> convolution is the imposition of a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrum" title=3D"Spectrum">spectr=
